# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
AS we have done in spiral-I,spiral-II their was not given from where to start so we assume 4 pointers top,bottom,left,right but in this it is mentioned from where to start so in this traverse matrix till size of resultant array is less than size of matix (rows*cols);

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Initialize len to 1 to represent the length of the current spiral.
Create an empty 2D vector ans to store the coordinates in the spiral.
Add the starting coordinate (rStart, cStart) to ans.
Enter a loop that continues until ans contains coordinates for all cells in the grid.
Inside the loop:
a. Move right by iterating i from 1 to len, adding valid coordinates to ans.
b. Update the y coordinate to the right boundary.
c. Move down by iterating i from 1 to len, adding valid coordinates to ans.
d. Update the x coordinate to the bottom boundary.
e. Increment len to increase the length of the spiral.
f. Move left by iterating i from 1 to len, adding valid coordinates to ans.
g. Update the y coordinate to the left boundary.
h. Move up by iterating i from 1 to len, adding valid coordinates to ans.
i. Update the x coordinate to the top boundary.
Repeat the above steps until ans contains coordinates for all cells in the grid.
Return the ans vector containing the spiral coordinates.
# This code essentially follows a clockwise spiral pattern, extending the spiral by increasing len and updating the boundary coordinates in each direction (right, down, left, up) until all cells are covered.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(n*m)  ; n=rows,m=cols
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(n*m) ; n=rows,m=cols
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

