Took me a while to understand @Wilmol's solution. I wanted to annotate the code so hopefully other's can find it useful.
First, understand what the union find (aka disjoint set) data structure is. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ID00PMy0-vE

Alright. Now that you know what it is, we can use a DSU and check if the query's start and end are in the same component.
Intuition: 
1) Sort the edges by weight.
2) For each query, construct our DSU with edges less than the query's weight.
3) The query's start and end will be connected if they are in the same DSU component. We can check by looking at their roots.
4) For optimization reasons, sort the queries by weight so that we don't have to rebuild the DSU from all edges for each query. This allows us to construct the DSU starting with the edge that violated the last query's weight.

```
class Solution {

    // This is used to evaluate only the edges that haven't yet been evaluated for the limit in the queries
    // We sort the queries by limit ascending so that we can start from where the limit was exceeded in the
    // previous query.
    int curr = 0;

    public boolean[] distanceLimitedPathsExist(int n, int[][] edges, int[][] queries) {
        // Sort edges  by ascending weight, this will let us stop checking the edges after it
        // violates the limit in the query.
        Arrays.sort(edges, (a, b) -> a[2] - b[2]);

        // We want to sort the queries by weight, so to retain the info of its ith index, we
        // create a new array that contains its index.
        int[][] qs = new int[queries.length][4];
        for (int i = 0; i < queries.length; i++) {
            qs[i][0] = queries[i][0];
            qs[i][1] = queries[i][1];
            qs[i][2] = queries[i][2];
            qs[i][3] = i;
        }
        Arrays.sort(qs, (a, b) -> a[2] - b[2]);

        int[] roots = new int[n];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) roots[i] = i; // Initialize the DSU

        // For each query, go through the edges and see if the two nodes are in the same component
        boolean[] res = new boolean[queries.length];
        for (int[] q : qs) { // n2 log n
            res[q[3]] = helper(edges, q[0], q[1], q[2], roots);
        }
        return res;
    }

    private boolean helper(int[][] edges, int start, int end, int limit, int[] roots) { // n log n
        // Start at curr, which is the last edge that violated the previous query's limit
        for (int i = curr; i < edges.length; i++) {
            int[] edge = edges[i];
            if (edge[2] >= limit) {
                // This edge is out of limit
                this.curr = i;
                break;
            }
            int edgeStartRoot = getRoot(roots, edge[0]);
            int edgeEndRoot = getRoot(roots, edge[1]);
            if (edgeStartRoot != edgeEndRoot) {
                // They don't have the same root, but clearly they're connected since they're an
                // edge. For this example, just update edgeEndRoot's root to be edgeStartRoot.
                roots[edgeEndRoot] = edgeStartRoot;
                // Note: we could've updated edgeStartRoot's root to be edgeEndRoot and it would
                // still work
                // roots[edgeStartRoot] = edgeEndRoot;
            }
        }
        // Since we only look at edges that are less than the limit, if the start and end
        // share the same root, it's in the same component, implying that there's a path
        // between them.
        return getRoot(roots, start) == getRoot(roots, end); // log n
    }

    private int getRoot(int[] roots, int node) {
        int temp = node;
        // Find the node that points to itself.
        while (roots[node] != node) {
            node = roots[node];
        }
        // Set the node's label as the node that points to itself.
        roots[temp] = node;
        return node;
    }
}
```

