# Intuition
First of all understand that we need to take the edges with the value less than the limit and not the final distance from source and destination. Had we needed to find that we could have applied Djisktra algo. But here we need to select edges such that their weight is less than the limit

# Approach
The only point now left in this DSU approach is to understand the need to sort. Basically we need to compute our answer for various different queries. Let's say we had a query where for the first query the limit is 10 and for the next one the limit is 5, now all the edges computed for limit 5 will again be computed for the limit 10 and vica versa. Hence to avoid this, we will first consider the lower limits and gradually consider the higher ones. Sorting the edges provide us with the flexibility to include the edges appropriately based on our limit value

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(n + e + q + eloge + qlogq)$$

- Space complexity:
$$O(n + q)$$

# Code
```
class DSU {
public:
    vector<int> parent, size;
    DSU(int n) {
        parent.resize(n + 1);
        size.resize(n + 1, 1);
        for(int i = 0; i <= n; i++) parent[i] = i;
    }
    int find(int x) {
        if(parent[x] == x) return x;
        return parent[x] = find(parent[x]);
    }
    void unionSize(int u, int v) {
        int uP = find(u), vP = find(v);
        if(uP == vP) return;
        if(size[uP] > size[vP]) {
            parent[vP] = uP;
            size[uP] += size[vP];
        } else {
            parent[uP] = vP;
            size[vP] += size[uP];
        }
    }
};
class Solution {
    bool static compare(const vector<int>& a, const vector<int>& b) {
        return a[2] < b[2];
    }
public:
    vector<bool> distanceLimitedPathsExist(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edgeList, vector<vector<int>>& queries) {
        int querySize = queries.size();
        DSU ds(n);
        vector<bool> ans(querySize);
        vector<vector<int>> newQ;
        int index = 0;
        for(auto& it : queries) {
            newQ.push_back({it[0], it[1], it[2], index});
            index++;
        }

        sort(edgeList.begin(), edgeList.end(), compare);
        sort(newQ.begin(), newQ.end(), compare);
