solutions.content:
Typical clustering problem and we might wish to play smart about it, since a brute force approach will clearly fail with numbers at hand.

We will "lazily" populate our clustering data structure, a Disjoint Set (AKA "Union Find"), so tht it will have only all the edges below the current query.

We can avoid re-populating the clusters from scratch all the time, if we proceed in increasing order, as explained in a bit.

But first, let's declare a few support variables:
* `eLen` and `qLen` will store the length of `edges` and `queries` respectively;
* `ePos` will be a pointer we will use to add edges lazily to our disjoint set;
* `lmt` and `resPos` are support variables we will use later with the queries;
* `uf` is our `UF` instance, initialised for the full range of `n`;
* `res` is our accumulator variable, preset to be of `qLen` cells to avoid reallocations.

Next we will sort both `edges` and `queries` by increasing distance, but not before having added the original position `i` to each query, not to lose that information.

Our class `UF` will have a constructor taking its expected size `n`, that will be stored in the variable `count` and used to fill the first `n` cells of `parent` so that each cell has a value equal to its index.

We will then create a standard `find` method that will `return` either:
* `node`, when its values matches `parent[node]` (ie: it is the head of a cluster);
* the recursive call to `find(parent[node])` otherwise, storing it in `parent[node]` itself.

Finally the `merge` method will take two nodes `n1` and `n2` and:
* convert them to the value of their respective parents;
* `return` if they are the same (ie: already part of the same cluster);
* make sure that `n1 < n2`, swapping the two values otherwise;
* set the `parent` of `n2` to be `n1`;
* every time we merge, we have one less cluster, so we decrease `count` by `1`.

Time for our main loop! For each query `q`, we will:
* store the original position of `q` (ie: `q[3]`) in `resPos`;
* if we are already in a situation that has every single node connected (ie: `uf.count == 1`), we will just:
    * set the matching cell `res[resPos]` to `true`;
    * `continue` with the loop;
* store the current distance limit (ie: `q[2]`) in `lmt`;
* loop `while` we still have edges to parse (ie: `ePos < eLen`) and their distance is within the limit (ie: `edges[ePos][2] < lmt`) and:
    * store the current edge `edges[ePos++]` in `currEdge` as a reference;
    * merge the nodes it connects in `uf`;
* set the matching cell `res[resPos]` to `true` if both queried nodes are in the same cluster (ie: `uf.find(q[0]) == uf.find(q[1])`), `false` otherwise.

Once done, we can `return` `res` :)

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(n)$

# Code
```cpp
struct UF {
    int parent[100000], count;
    UF(int n) {
        // preparing count and parent
        count = n;
        iota(parent, parent + n, 0);
    }
    int find(int node) {
        return node == parent[node] ? node : parent[node] = find(parent[node]);
    }
    void merge(int n1, int n2) {
        // turning n1 and n2 into their parents
        n1 = find(n1), n2 = find(n2);
        // nodes are already part of the same cluster
        if (n1 == n2) return;
        // making sure n1 < n2
        if (n1 > n2) swap(n1, n2);
        parent[n2] = n1, count--;
    }
};

class Solution {
public:
    vector<bool> distanceLimitedPathsExist(int n, vector<vector<int>> &edges, vector<vector<int>> &queries) {
        // support variables
        int eLen = edges.size(), qLen = queries.size(), ePos = 0, lmt, resPos;
        UF uf(n);
        vector<bool> res(qLen);
        // preparing edges and queries
        sort(begin(edges), end(edges), [](auto &a, auto&b){return a[2] < b[2];});
        for (int i = 0; i < qLen; i++) queries[i].push_back(i);
        sort(begin(queries), end(queries), [](auto &a, auto&b){return a[2] < b[2];});
        // parsing queries
        for (auto &q: queries) {
            resPos = q[3];
            // all nodes are already connected
            if (uf.count == 1) {
                res[resPos] = true;
                continue;
            }
            // adding all edges that are still < lmt
            lmt = q[2];
            while (ePos < eLen && edges[ePos][2] < lmt) {
                auto &currEdge = edges[ePos++];
                uf.merge(currEdge[0], currEdge[1]);
            }
            // checking if both nodes are now in the same cluster
            res[resPos] = uf.find(q[0]) == uf.find(q[1]);
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Aternative version with a boolean flag to stop the main loop when we have connected all the nodes already, after having initialised `res` to be all `true`s - it runs a bit faster:

```cpp
