# Intuition
First thought might be to use a graph traversal algorithm finding *max edge len* paths between nodes. However, the constraints of 10^5 nodes, edges, and queries makes this unfeasible. For these types of constraints **we need an O(n*log n) algorithm. Which means we can do sorting and union-find**.

The next insight is **when we process a query with the max len of K we only need to look at edges of len < K**. If there's a path between two nodes using only such edges then this path has a max edge len < K.

# Approach

1. Order all edges by their length;
2. Order all queries by their max length. Make sure to record the original index of the query.
3. Create an empty union-find for `n` vertices.
4. Process queries in the order of increasing max len from step 2. For query (`from`, `to`, `maxLen`, `idx`):
    a. Use all edges with len < `maxLen` to connect their respective nodes in the union-find data structure.
    b. Use union-find to check if `from` and `to` belong to the same group. If they do, then there exists a path in the original graph with edges of length < `maxLen`.
    c. Use the result from step b. to record an answer to query `idx`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n * log n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    static record Q(int from, int to, int len, int idx) {}

    public boolean[] distanceLimitedPathsExist(int n, int[][] edgeList, int[][] queries) {
        Arrays.sort(edgeList, (a, b) -> a[2] - b[2]); // sort edges by the distance
        Q[] qs = new Q[queries.length];
        for (int i = 0; i < queries.length; i++) {
            qs[i] = new Q(queries[i][0], queries[i][1], queries[i][2], i);
        }
        // sort queries by the max len
        Arrays.sort(qs, (a, b) -> a.len - b.len);

        boolean[] result = new boolean[queries.length];
        var uf = new UnionFind(n);
        int nextEdge = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < qs.length; i++) {
            var q = qs[i];

            // add all edges with len < q.len to see which nodes are connectible
            // with a path with only edges of len < q.len
            while (nextEdge < edgeList.length && edgeList[nextEdge][2] < q.len) {
                uf.union(edgeList[nextEdge][0], edgeList[nextEdge][1], edgeList[nextEdge][2]);
                nextEdge++;
            }

            int r1 = uf.findRepr(q.from);
            int r2 = uf.findRepr(q.to);

            result[q.idx] = r1 == r2;
        }

        return result;
    }

    static class UnionFind {
        private final int size;
        private final int[] groupRepr;
        private final int[] groupSize;

        public UnionFind(int size) {
            this.size = size;
            groupRepr = new int[size];
            for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
                groupRepr[i] = i;
            }
            groupSize = new int[size];
            Arrays.fill(groupSize, 1);
        }

        public int findRepr(int node) {
            while (groupRepr[node] != node) {
                node = groupRepr[node];
            }
            return node;
        }

        public void union(int n1, int n2, int len) {
            int n1g = findRepr(n1);
            int n2g = findRepr(n2);
            if (n1g == n2g) {
                return;
            }

            int smallerG = groupSize[n1g] < groupSize[n1g] ? n1g : n2g;
            int largerG = groupSize[n1g] < groupSize[n1g] ? n2g : n1g;

            groupRepr[smallerG] = largerG;
            groupSize[largerG] += groupSize[smallerG];
        }
    }
}
```

