	/*
    Advantage of using DisjointSet: It gives access to check if two nodes exists in graph or
                                    same component by checking its ultimate parent in O(1) time.


    WHY CAN'T WE USE DFS OR BFS HERE TO CHECK EDGE WEIGHT FOR EVERY NODE
        but are using DisjointSet Union...   

    As, it will give TLE for calling DFS/BFS for every Query.

    So, instead of checking for every node,





    Solution 1:  Simple DFS again and again  (TLE)

     time:   O(N+E) * O(N+E) = O(N^2)

    1.) Pick first query, call DFS and check every edge till destination if it has
        dist > limit.
    2.) Do same for all queries.



    OPTIMISED APPROACH:

    Intuition: Jo edges ka distance kamm hai unko hi pehle tackle kro aur increasing order
                me aise hi chlte chlo.

    1.) To maintain order in final answer, Add original index to the every query coz 
        in next step we are going to sort.

    2.) First sort all queries in increasing order of Distance to evaluate 
        nodes having smaller distance first.

    3.) Take first query, pick distance from it, (union all the nodes)/ (Connect all nodes)
        / (make graph for all nodes) having distance smaller than its limit 
        After union, just check if(both nodes exists) answer for that query is true.

    This will save your time and u can check existence of two nodes in O(1) time.
